<div id="review_1541235147" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1541235147" />
    <a title="farith" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/31454912-farith"><img alt="farith" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1583134079p2/31454912.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1541235147?book_show_action=true">Mar 07, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="farith" class="user" itemprop="url" name="farith" href="/user/show/31454912-farith">farith</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/31454912-farith?shelf=lgbt">lgbt</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/31454912-farith?shelf=read-in-english">read-in-english</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1541235147" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3790196811030799952"><b>2.5 stars.</b><br/><br/><i>&quot;If there&apos;s no feeling of fear, then there&apos;s no need for courage.&quot;</i><br/><br/>This is the first time that I read a David Levithan book and well, this is disappointing.<br/>I didn&apos;t really have expectations from the book but still hoped to liked it. You know, there&apos;s always those short contemporaries that makes you feel butterflies and it&apos;s like you&apos;re in love again for the first time. <b>This wasn&apos;t that kind of book.</b> <br/><br/>In this book I wanted to kill everyone. I hated everybody! Ok, maybe not EVERYBODY, but </span>
  <span id="freeText3790196811030799952" style="display:none"><b>2.5 stars.</b><br><br><i>"If there's no feeling of fear, then there's no need for courage."</i><br><br>This is the first time that I read a David Levithan book and well, this is disappointing.<br>I didn't really have expectations from the book but still hoped to liked it. You know, there's always those short contemporaries that makes you feel butterflies and it's like you're in love again for the first time. <b>This wasn't that kind of book.</b> <br><br>In this book I wanted to kill everyone. I hated everybody! Ok, maybe not EVERYBODY, but almost. The only character who, I think saved the book for me, was Noah. Ah Noah. I'll talk about him later. First thing first: Paul, our MC. <br><br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1490766750ra/22341600.gif" class="gr-hostedUserImg"> <br><br>Paul was the most annoying thing I've read in the LGBT contemporary books I've gone through. He was so undecided about what he really wanted. <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[I mean come on, you LOVE Noah, but your ex returns begging for forgiveness and shit and you give him priority? I understand the "message" David Levithan wanted to give there, about forgiveness and how pass is not important anymore, BUT DAMN PAUL DROVE ME INSANE WHILE HE TRIED DOING THIS! Here are some examples about it.<br>After Kyle kisses him and he still wanted to be with Noah:<br><br><i>"'Do you regret it?' he asks, after I haven't responded.<br><br>'No,' I say, even though I do"</i><br><br>UGH I WANTED TO KILL PAUL ALL THE TIME.<br><br>Also when he fucked up with Noah and was with Kyle, and Paul just nicely says to Kyle <i>"Don't worry about it."</i> No. Man, if I were Paul, I'd tell Kyle that he should fucking <b>worry,</b> that it's NOT OK, and that he should leave him alone.<br> <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br><br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1490766750ra/22341601.gif" class="gr-hostedUserImg"> <br><br>Then there are a lot of other characters that were so meh, I didn't care for them at all, the book was full of clichés. Like Infinite Darlene, sometimes she was there just to <b>ANNOY</b> me. Also, what's up with the whole transgender girl as a quarterback of a football team? The book is unrealistic and I don't like the way David Levithan talked about homosexuality. It's too unrealistic, that's the only word I can think of at the moment. <b>Unrealistic.</b><br><br>Levithan's writing just wasn't my thing and I don't really know if I will pick one of his other works up soon. Maybe never to be honest.<br><br>The finale was opened af and that bothered me a lot because they never resolved ANYTHING.<br><br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1490766750ra/22341602.gif" class="gr-hostedUserImg"> <br><br>Ok, but right now I'm going to talk about Noah, the only one I cared about. I know he's character was super cheesy and a total LGBT cliché but I couldn't resist to like him a lot and feel the urge to hug him for the rest of the book.<br><br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1465756438ra/19397323.gif" class="gr-hostedUserImg"> <br><br>The scene I liked the most was when Noah comes over Paul's for the first time and well, things happen. It was super cute. And ugh, Noah. He was perfect.<br><br><b>"I lean forward and kiss him. The flowers crush between our shirts. I touch his lips, I breathe him in. I close my eyes, I open them. He is surprised, I can tell. I am surprised too. He kisses me back with a kiss like a smile."</b><br><br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1490766750ra/22341599.gif" class="gr-hostedUserImg"></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></span>
  <a data-text-id="3790196811030799952" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

